Overview

The EyeMD EMR FHIR API enables connection to customer systems using the FHIR (Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources) standard for healthcare resources. This standard allows application developers to securely create products and exchange clinical data in a consistent, flexible, and easy-to-implement manner.

The FHIR API is available for customers using EyeMD EMR version 2.0 or later. It supports FHIR Release 4 (R4) and adheres to the United States Core Data for Interoperability (US Core) v1 guidelines and requirements for data sharing.

General Information

SMART on FHIR

The API meets the requirements of the Standardized API for Patient and Population Services criterion §170.315(g)(10) in the 2015 Edition Cures Update. The API supports both SMART App Launch and SMART Backend Services v2.0.0. For more information, please visit https://hl7.org/fhir/smart-app-launch/.

Supported Application Types

  1. Patient Apps

  2. Practitioner Apps (for Healthcare Providers / Practices)

  3. Backend System Apps

FHIR Server Capability Metadata

Capability metadata can be queried by appending "/metadata" to the Endpoint Service Base URL.

Patients

Patients interested in connecting to the API using a SMART on FHIR capable app can do so by logging in to their provider's patient portal, scrolling down to the "API Access" section, and clicking the "Request Access" button. They will then be prompted to authenticate using a Microsoft Live account. If the patient does not have a Microsoft Live account, they will be prompted to enter a code sent to the email they provide in the authentication form.

Healthcare Providers / Practices

To make patient data accessible via the FHIR API, some setup is required. First, your IT team must configure a port forward on your router to the EMR Gateway Server port. After this is done, EyeMD EMR will configure the FHIR API server to communicate with your Gateway server. To initiate this process, please contact Customer Service.

Application Vendors

Third-party application vendors interested in accessing the API must first complete a one-time Application Registration Request. Once the registration request is received, it will be processed within 10 days.

To register your App:

  1. Navigate to https://www.eyemdemr.com/fhir

  2. Review the API Documentation and agree to the Terms and Conditions.

  3. Complete the SMART on FHIR Application Registration Request form.

Once your registration request is processed, we will send an email response to the supplied email address within 5 days. If your registration request is approved, your app will be registered and enabled, and you will receive an email that includes your credentials and configuration details. If your registration request is denied, you will receive an email with the stated reason for denial. If your request is denied more than 5 times for any reason, further requests will no longer be processed and will be discarded.

For more information, see the Application Registration Requirement section below.

Fees

Patients: Patients are not charged any fees to access their data using the FHIR API.

Practice: Practices using EyeMD EMR are charged a one-time FHIR setup fee of $300 to recover costs associated with integrating their local EMR instance to the FHIR API server. Ongoing throttled access to the API is included as part of the Patient Portal Subscription.

Application Vendors: Application vendors are charged a one-time setup fee of $3,000 to recover costs associated with identity verification and registering the vendor as an approved application vendor. Vendors can request live API support for an additional $2,000. Once approved, the application vendor can make up to 300 API requests per endpoint per day for data authorized by any EyeMD EMR provider or patient. Requests exceeding this limit may be denied or rate-limited. Additional transactions are available on a quoted basis.

Setup Instructions

Patients:

1. Login in to your EyeMD EMR Patient Web Portal.

2. Scroll down to the bottom of the Page and press the button "Request Access".

3. You will then see the following message that indicates your are now ready to start using Smart Apps.

Practices:

1. First, you must be logged in the EMR as an Administrator or Doctor to the practice.

2. At the main patient flow select the menu button.

3. Then select the menu choices as shown below, Options - Integration - Interface Options.

4. Scroll to the bottom of the screen and press the + sign to add an app.

5. Fill in the fields as described below, and select the checkbox for "Practitioner" (used for an app that presents the data for all patients) or select the checkbox for "Patient" (used for an app that presents data for a specific patient). Then press save.

6. The smart app will now be listed in the screen where you originally added it with the + sign. Press save and then at the main patient flow screen you will see a FHIR icon and you are now done.

The API defaults to returning 10 records at a time. If more records are available, a url will be included in the response which can be used to retrieve the next set of records. The url can be found in the link array and is identified with the relation of "next".

You can change the amount of returned records by defining the_count property as a parameter.

{{base}}/Patient?_count=30

Search

Search Parameter Types

Each search parameter is defined by a type that specifies how the search parameter behaves. These are the defined parameter types:

number Search parameter SHALL be a number (a whole number, or a decimal).
date Search parameter is on a date/time. The date format is the standard XML format, though other formats may be supported.
string Search parameter is a simple string, like a name part. Search is case-insensitive and accent-insensitive. May match just the start of a string. String parameters may contain spaces.
token Search parameter on a coded element or identifier. May be used to search through the text, display, code and code/codesystem (for codes) and label, system and key (for identifier). Its value is either a string or a pair of namespace and value, separated by a "
reference A reference to another resource (Reference or canonical).
composite A composite search parameter that combines a search on two values together.
quantity A search parameter that searches on a quantity.
uri A search parameter that searches on a URI (RFC 3986).
special Special logic applies to this parameter per the description of the search parameter.

Used to get the SDOH questionnaire answers. https://www.hl7.org/fhir/searchparameter-registry.html#QuestionnaireResponse

Parameter Type Description
author reference The author of the questionnaire response (fhir.hl7.org)
authored date When the questionnaire response was last changed (fhir.hl7.org)
based-on reference Plan/proposal/order fulfilled by this questionnaire response (fhir.hl7.org)
encounter reference QuestionnaireResponse: Encounter associated with the questionnaire response (fhir.hl7.org)
identifier token QuestionnaireResponse: The unique identifier for the questionnaire response (fhir.hl7.org)
item-subject reference Search by item value where the item has isSubject=true (fhir.hl7.org)
part-of reference Procedure or observation this questionnaire response was performed as part of (fhir.hl7.org)
patient reference The patient that is the subject of the questionnaire response (fhir.hl7.org)
questionnaire reference The questionnaire the answers are provided for (fhir.hl7.org)
source reference The individual providing the information reflected in the response (fhir.hl7.org)
status token The status of the questionnaire response (fhir.hl7.org)
subject reference The subject of the questionnaire response (fhir.hl7.org)

request.description:
Please Note:

  1. All parameters are nullable and will return all Encounters for all Patients.
  2. The [date] parameter ONLY supports gt (greater than), lt (less than), eq (equal to). Only the first two date parameters will be considered, and the earliest value must appear first in the query string.
Use this method to get specific Encounter data

item.name: Specimen

request.description: Use the get method to retrieve a specific lab result.

item.description:
Used to get a lab speciman. https://www.hl7.org/fhir/searchparameter-registry.html#Speciman

Parameter Type Description
accession token The accession number associated with the specimen (hl7.org)
bodysite reference Reference to a resource (by instance) where the specimen was collected from a body site (e.g., body structure) (hl7.org)
collected date The date the specimen was collected (hl7.org)
collector reference Who collected the specimen (hl7.org)
container-device reference The unique identifier associated with the specimen container (hl7.org)
identifier token The unique identifier associated with the specimen (hl7.org)
parent reference The parent of the specimen (hierarchical grouping) (hl7.org)
patient reference The patient the specimen comes from (hl7.org)
procedure reference The procedure that collected the specimen (hl7.org)
status token The status of the specimen (e.g., available, unavailable, unsatisfactory, entered-in-error) (hl7.org)
subject reference The subject of the specimen (e.g., Patient, Group, Device, Substance) (hl7.org)
type token The specimen type (hl7.org)
